{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":5301,"record_hash":"sha256:564869e422aefe56bcb090081e15e9b84d077ffd23232d64b682b2a1f8da0995","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:31:35.692Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"::code-comment{title=\"[P2] Sensitive field names do not force redaction\" body=\"`field_name` is currently used only for exemptions, so values under keys like `password`, `token`, `api_key`, `authorization`, or `secret` can still be stored unchanged when they are short, low-entropy, dictionary-like, or UUID-shaped. A tiny local denylist before the entropy/UUID/path exemptions would close this without turning the POC into a full scanner.\" file=\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\" start=118 end=124 priority=2 confidence=0.87}\n\n::code-comment{title=\"[P2] Generic Git labels can preserve random hex\" body=\"`protected_git_hash_range()` treats field names like `object`, `parent`, `tree`, and `blob` as Git-labelled context. In arbitrary JSON payloads those names are not necessarily Git-specific, so a 40/64-char random-looking hex secret under one of those fields can be preserved instead of redacted. Narrowing field-name preservation to more explicit `*_sha`, `*_oid`, or `object_id`-style labels would make the exception tighter.\" file=\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\" start=320 end=325 priority=2 confidence=0.79}\n\n::code-comment{title=\"[P2] Embedded UUIDs are preserved inside risky tokens\" body=\"`protected_spans()` preserves any UUID range even when the surrounding candidate is being redacted. The existing `sk-<uuid>-<random>` case stores the UUID portion, which can leak tenant/session/account identifiers for token formats that embed UUIDs. A stricter POC rule would preserve UUIDs only when the whole candidate is a UUID or when it has an approved ID label.\" file=\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\" start=173 end=176 priority=2 confidence=0.78}\n\nThis pass did not produce new P1s. The cleanup reviewer is now repeating small shape nits only (`CandidateRedaction`, `is_obvious_non_secret`, doc/derive polish), so structurally we’re close to equilibrium. The remaining real findings are privacy policy choices around field-name deny/allow lists and embedded identifier preservation. Local checks passed: `cargo test -p but-agentlog redaction --lib` and `cargo clippy -p but-agentlog --all-targets --no-deps`.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:31:35.692Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}